node.title: Creating mesh of dicretization sizes in the same file
node.bodyText:
Hello,
I would like to have a mesh discretization like

My idea is to use different quadrature rules in the meshes and thus, I need to identify each region by some IDs.
How best do I do that?
Thank you

Hello
You could start with selective refinement using either of these mesh generators in 1D
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/meshgenerators/RefineBlockGenerator.html
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/meshgenerators/RefineSidesetGenerator.html
If you do want to do selective quadratures instead, then the syntax is shown here
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/actions/SetupQuadratureAction.html
For both options, you ll want to create different subdomains
Guillaume

node.title: Installing Moose on HPC
node.bodyText:
Hello, I have successfully installed the PETsc and built the mesh and am running with gnu8.3, openmpi 3.1.4 and python 3.8 but when I go to run tests, I am getting several "FAILED (EXPECTED ERROR MISSING)" lines.
Attached is the full script.
test issues.txt
Thanks for any help.

Hello
the errors are pointing to MPI libraries being inconsistent between the ones you used to build the code and one used by the test suite to run the code
there s other threads on this forum about slurm/ srun issues if you want to check them out
Guillaume

Hello, thank you for the information. Apologies in advance as I am very new at this.
Could you potentially elaborate or point me in a more concrete direction to potentially help resolve this?

Can you please paste the output of the diagnostics script in moose/scripts?
Did you run the test suite in the same node and same session as when you built the codes?
I'm asking because I want to make sure the environment is consistent between when the code was installed and run

Here is the diagnostics script.
`write_to_stdout() {
  echo -e "$@"
}

file_born_date() {
  if [ -f $1 ]; then
    if [ `uname` == "Darwin" ]; then
      echo `stat -f "%Sm" -t "%Y-%m-%d %H:%M" "$1"`
    else
      echo `date -d @$(stat -c %Y "$1") +%Y-%m-%d\ %H:%M`
    fi
  fi
}

diagnose_compilers() {
    # Variable
    which $CC &> /dev/null
    if [ "$?" -eq 0 ]; then
        write_to_stdout "\nVariable \`which \$CC\` check:\n`which $CC`\n\n\$CC --version:\n`$CC --version`"
    else
        write_to_stdout "\n\$CC not set"
    fi

    # Static
    which mpicc &> /dev/null
    if [ "$?" -eq 0 ]; then
        write_to_stdout "\nMPICC:\nwhich mpicc:\n\t`which mpicc`\nmpicc -show:\n\t`mpicc -show`\n\nCOMPILER `echo $(mpicc -show | cut -d\  -f1)`:\n`$(mpicc -show | cut -d\  -f1) --version`"
    else
        write_to_stdout "\nMPICC WRAPPER NOT FOUND"
    fi
}

diagnose_modules() {
    type module &> /dev/null
    if [ "$?" -eq 0 ]; then
        write_to_stdout "\nMODULES:\n`module list 2>&1`"
    else
        write_to_stdout "\nMODULES NOT AVAILABLE"
    fi
}

diagnose_root() {
    if [ $(id -u) = 0 ]; then write_to_stdout "RUNNING AS ROOT"; fi
}

diagnose_environment() {
    write_to_stdout "\nENVIRONMENT:\n`env`"
}

diagnose_cpus() {
    if [ `uname` == "Darwin" ]; then
        CPUS=`/usr/sbin/sysctl -n hw.ncpu`
    else
        CPUS=`cat /proc/cpuinfo | grep processor | wc -l`
    fi
    write_to_stdout "\nCPU Count: `echo $CPUS`"
}

diagnose_memory() {
    if [ `uname` == "Darwin" ]; then
        PAGE_SIZE=`vm_stat | grep "page size of" | sed 's/[^0-9]*//g'`
        MEMORY_FREE=`vm_stat | grep free | awk -v page_size=$PAGE_SIZE '{ print (page_size * $3) / 1048576}'`
    else
        MEMORY_FREE=`awk '/MemFree/ { printf "%.3f \n", $2/1024 }' /proc/meminfo`
    fi
    write_to_stdout "\nMemory Free: `echo $MEMORY_FREE` MB"
}

diagnose_arch() {
    if [ `uname` == "Darwin" ]; then
        SYSTEM=`uname -v`
    else
        which lsb_release &> /dev/null
        if [ "$?" -eq 0 ]; then
            SYSTEM="`lsb_release -a`"
        else
            if [ -f /etc/system-release ]; then
                SYSTEM="`cat /etc/system-release`"
            else
                SYSTEM="Not Available"
            fi
        fi
    fi
    write_to_stdout "\nSystem Arch: `echo $SYSTEM`"
}

diagnose_package_version() {
    if [ -f /opt/moose/build ]; then
        write_to_stdout "\nMOOSE Package Version: `cat /opt/moose/build | sed 's/[^0-9]*//g'`"
    else
        write_to_stdout "\nMOOSE Package Version: Custom Build"
    fi
}

diagnose_python() {
    which python &> /dev/null
    if [ "$?" -eq 0 ]; then
        write_to_stdout "\nPython:\n\t`which python`\n\t`python --version 2>&1`"
    else
        write_to_stdout "\nPython: NO PYTHON DETECTED"
    fi
}

diagnose_petsc() {
    if [ -f "$PETSC_DIR/include/petscconfiginfo.h" ]; then
        formatted=`cat $PETSC_DIR/include/petscconfiginfo.h | sed -e 's|\\\||g'`
        write_to_stdout "\nPETSc configure:\n$formatted"
        write_to_stdout "\nPETSc linked libraries:"

        if [ `uname` = "Linux" ]; then
            ldd $PETSC_DIR/lib/libpetsc.so
        else
            otool -L $PETSC_DIR/lib/libpetsc.dylib
        fi

    elif [ -z "$PETSC_DIR" ]; then
        write_to_stdout "\nPETSC_DIR not set"
    fi
}

# Execute the diagnostics
date
diagnose_root
diagnose_arch
diagnose_package_version
diagnose_cpus
diagnose_memory
diagnose_compilers
diagnose_python
diagnose_modules
diagnose_petsc
diagnose_environment

The moose install aspect prior to the PETSc step was done on a different day but compiling PETSc and the libmesh was all done at once on the same node.
Thank you again
oh you should run the script not paste the script please

node.title: Power law creep material
node.bodyText:
Hi,
I am very much new to MOOSE, and was trying the PowerLawCreepStressUpdate material to simulate a simple creep simulation on a block (as a start). So my geometry is a box with bottom face fixed and I am applying on the top a stress (pressure) load of -10e6.
I used power_law_creep.i as my reference for input (also attached).
Now the material parameters for this are: E=2e11; nu = 0.3, (elastic) and A=1e-14; n=1; and Q=0.0 (creep). So if I impose an average stress of 10MPa, then I would expect the elastic strain to be ~5e-5 and creep strain to be ~1e-8. However, when I am looking at my results, I see that the effective creep strain is 0
Am I missing something ? (apologies in advance for a relatively stupid question :( )
This is my result:

And this is my input file:
[GlobalParams]
  displacements = 'disp_x disp_y disp_z'
[]

[Mesh]
  file=box_geom.e
[]

[Variables]
  [temp]
    order = FIRST
    family = LAGRANGE
    initial_condition = 1523.0
  []
[]

[Functions]
  [top_pull]
    type = PiecewiseLinear
    x = '0 1'
    y = '1 1'
  []
[]


[Modules/TensorMechanics/Master]
  [all]
    strain = FINITE
    incremental = true
    add_variables = true
    generate_output = 'stress_yy creep_strain_xx creep_strain_yy creep_strain_zz elastic_strain_yy'
  []
[]

[Kernels]
  [heat]
    type = Diffusion
    variable = temp
  []
[]


[BCs]
  [top_load_pressure]
    type = Pressure
    variable = disp_y
    boundary = top_y_load
    factor = -10.0e6
    function = top_pull
  []
  [bottom_fix_y]
    type = DirichletBC
    variable = disp_y
    boundary = bot_y_fixed
    value = 0.0
  []
  [bottom_fix_x]
    type = DirichletBC
    variable = disp_x
    boundary = bot_y_fixed
    value = 0.0
  []
  [bottom_fix_z]
    type = DirichletBC
    variable = disp_z
    boundary = bot_y_fixed
    value = 0.0
  []
[]

[Materials]
  [elasticity_tensor]
    type = ComputeIsotropicElasticityTensor
    youngs_modulus = 2e11
    poissons_ratio = 0.3
  []
  [radial_return_stress]
    type = ComputeMultipleInelasticStress
    inelastic_models = 'power_law_creep'
    tangent_operator = elastic
  []
  [power_law_creep]
    type = PowerLawCreepStressUpdate
    coefficient = 1e-14
    n_exponent = 1
    activation_energy = 0.0
    absolute_tolerance = 1e-6
    relative_tolerance = 1e-6
    temperature = temp
  []
[]

[AuxVariables]
  [./aux_creep_strain]
    order = CONSTANT
    family = MONOMIAL
  [../]
  [./vM_elastic_strain]
    order = CONSTANT
    family = MONOMIAL
  [../]  
  [./von_mises_stress]
	#Dependent variable used to visualize the Von Mises stress
    order = CONSTANT
    family = MONOMIAL
  [../]

[]

[AuxKernels]
  [./creep_aux]
    type = MaterialRealAux
    variable = aux_creep_strain
    property = effective_creep_strain
    execute_on = timestep_end
  [../]
  [./elastic_strain_aux]
    type = RankTwoScalarAux
    variable = vM_elastic_strain
    rank_two_tensor = elastic_strain
    scalar_type = VonMisesStress
    execute_on = timestep_end
  [../]
  [./von_mises_kernel_stress]
   #Calculates the von mises stress and assigns it to von_mises_stress
    type = RankTwoScalarAux
    variable = von_mises_stress
    rank_two_tensor = stress
    execute_on = timestep_end
    scalar_type = VonMisesStress
  [../]
[]

[Preconditioning]
  [smp]
    type = SMP
    full = true
  []
[]

[Executioner]
  type = Transient

  solve_type = 'Newton'

  start_time = 0.0
  dt    = 1.0
  dtmax = 2.0
  dtmin = 0.1
  nl_abs_tol = 1e-6
  end_time = 1
 []

[Outputs]
  print_linear_residuals = true
  perf_graph = true
  csv = true
  [./out]
    type = Exodus
    elemental_as_nodal = true
  [../]
  [./console]
    type = Console
    max_rows = 25
  [../]
[]

Actually, I changed the tolerance in the power law stress update to 1e-11, and now I get proper solution.

I am closing this issue
A possibly better solution is to set nl_forced_its = 1 in the [Executioner].

node.title: Which -pc_type is used in this step?
node.bodyText:
Hello everyone!
May I ask a question? In PJFNK, the last step we get

We want to get

Which -pc_type is used in this step?
Thank you very much !

The default preconditioner in serial is ILU (https://petsc.org/release/docs/manualpages/PC/PCILU/) and the default preconditioner in parallel is block jacobi (https://petsc.org/release/docs/manualpages/PC/PCBJACOBI/) with ILU on sub-blocks (individual processes)

At first glance, we don't currently support PETSc 3.18 (that is coming soon - I am tasked with getting that done), and it appears as though your PETSc configuration isn't configured in quite the same way as ours (for one, SLEPc is missing, but there could be other differences that aren't as obvious). I would first unload your petsc module:
module unload petsc

and then clean your MOOSE installation (this will delete files that you don't have committed, so be careful!)
git clean -xfd

And then build PETSc and libmesh manually:
cd /blue/michael.tonks/v.yadav/MOOSEInstallation/project2023/moose
scripts/update_and_rebuild_petsc.sh
scripts/update_and_rebuild_libmesh.sh
cd test
make -j24
./run_tests -j24

While the error you are receiving now is related to a missing Python module, these two PATH environment variables concerns me:
(edited for easy viewing)
LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/apps/gcc/9.3.0/openmpi/4.1.1/vtk/9.2.6/lib64:
/apps/compilers/intel/2020/0.166/mkl/lib/intel64:

/apps/mpi/gcc/9.3.0/openmpi/4.1.1/lib64/openmpi:
/apps/mpi/gcc/9.3.0/openmpi/4.1.1/lib64:
/opt/slurm/lib64:lib:
/apps/compilers/gcc/9.3.0/lib64::

The first path is to VTK built by an OpenMPI wrapper (which was also built by GCC), the second and third paths includes MPI libraries from Intel. It isn't until we reach the 4th path, that it is your OpenMPI wrapper.
(edited for easy viewing)
PATH=/apps/gcc/9.3.0/openmpi/4.1.1/vtk/9.2.6/bin:
/apps/mpi/gcc/9.3.0/openmpi/4.1.1/bin:
/apps/compilers/gcc/9.3.0/bin:
/apps/ufrc/bin:
/opt/slurm/bin:
/usr/lib64/qt-3.3/bin:
/usr/local/bin:/usr/bin:/usr/local/sbin:/usr/sbin:/opt/puppetlabs/bin:/bin:/opt/dell/srvadmin/bin:/home/v.yadav/bin

The first path correctly corresponds to the the first PATH in LD_LIBRARY_PATH, but the second path corresponds to your OpenMPI GCC MPI wrapper.
This is what I would consider a not-sane environment. You will be using a GCC built OpenMPI binary (which mpicc), but will be linking to Intel MPI libraries.

/usr/bin/ld: warning: libpmi2.so.0, needed by /apps/mpi/gcc/9.3.0/openmpi/4.1.1/lib64/libmpi_usempif08.so, may conflict with libpmi2.so.1
/usr/bin/ld: warning: libpmi.so.0, needed by /apps/mpi/gcc/9.3.0/openmpi/4.1.1/lib64/libmpi_usempif08.so, may conflict with libpmi.so.1

Also, I get following warning multiple times  during build libmesh step:
libtool: warning: '/blue/michael.tonks/v.yadav/MOOSEInstallation/project2023/moose/scripts/../petsc/arch-moose/lib/libhdf5_hl.la' seems to be moved
libtool: warning: '/apps/compilers/gcc/9.3.0/lib64/libgfortran.la' seems to be moved
libtool: warning: '/apps/compilers/gcc/9.3.0/lib64/libquadmath.la' seems to be moved
libtool: warning: '/apps/compilers/gcc/9.3.0/lib64/libstdc++.la' seems to be moved
libtool: warning: '/blue/michael.tonks/v.yadav/MOOSEInstallation/project2023/moose/scripts/../petsc/arch-moose/lib/libhdf5.la' seems to be moved
libtool: warning: '/apps/compilers/gcc/9.3.0/lib/gcc/x86_64-pc-linux-gnu/9.3.0/../../../../lib64/libstdc++.la' seems to be moved

I hope that these warning are not serious.

All these library "move/may conflict with" issues are direct results of your PATH being set in such a way as to use GNU GCC binaries, but then allowing objects to link to Intel libraries (we call this a not sane environment)
Going over this thread again, I see the following modules are being loaded:
Currently Loaded Modules:
  1) ufrc   2) gcc/9.3.0   3) openmpi/4.1.1   4) mkl/2020.0.166   5) vtk/9.2.6   6) moose/20230318

And with this new information:

and HPC admin installed 'packaging' and 'moose-pyhit' python packages for Python3.10. Now it is working.

If your admin installed moose-pyhit that means they installed Conda. This is not the correct procedure for an HPC Cluster. Is that what that last module is for (6) moose/20230318)? Does this module load up a valid PETSc/libMesh/Conda (moose-pyhit) combination or something?
My advice, since your building PETSc and libMesh yourself anyway (or rather, you should be. Its a safer bet to build vetted versions using our scripts/update_and_rebuild_petsc|libmesh) is to avoid loading the moose module altogether (which should prevent loading the Intel MKL module). I would start with openmpi/4.1.1 instead, and supply your own Python 3.x libraries with a basic install of Conda on your own terms.
The gist of what I would do if I was operating on your cluster:

Install my own Python, using Mambaforge:

cd ~/
module purge
curl -L -O https://github.com/conda-forge/miniforge/releases/latest/download/Mambaforge-Linux-x86_64.sh
bash Mambaforge-Linux-x86_64.sh -b -p ~/mambaforge3
export PATH=$HOME/mambaforge3/bin:$PATH
mamba init
Exit the terminal, launch it again. From here, you should have a basic modern Python interpreter. No need for anyone to install moose-pyhit.
2. Install Packaging
mamba install packaging

Load up the cluster's OpenMPI module:

module load openmpi/4.1.1
export CC=mpicc CXX=mpicxx FC=mpif90 F90=mpif90 F77=mpif77
# I like to export these, because many clusters do not do this for you when loading MPI modules

Try to build PETSc/libMesh/Moose

cd ~/projects/moose
export MOOSE_JOBS=6 METHODS=opt
scripts/update_and_rebuild_petsc.sh
# assuming the above succeeded
scripts/update_and_rebuild_libmesh.sh
# assuming the above succeeded
cd test
make -j 6
./run_tests -j 6

node.title: Questions about ODE definition
node.bodyText:
Hi all,
I am now thinking of a lump parameter problem (or scalar variable problem), of which ODE can be simplified into the following form:
$$A \cdot \frac{d(X \cdot Y)}{dt}=B \cdot F(X)\cdot G(Y)\quad when \quad X>a$$
$$A ^ { \prime } \cdot \frac { d ( X \cdot Y ) } { d t } = B ^ { \prime } \cdot F ^ { \prime } ( X ) \cdot G ^ { \prime } ( Y ) \quad when  \quad a \lt X \lt b$$
There are two variables $X$ and $Y$, and the remaining parameters $A$ and $B$ or the functions $F$ and $G$ are known, and $t$ is time. In order to close this ODE, an equation is added as
$$\xi(Y)=\chi(X)$$
The definition of general time-varying equations in MOOSE should be relatively convenient, directly through the ScalarKernels system. And if the ODE changes with time $t$, it should be realized through the Controls system. However, in the problem I studied, the ODE changes with the variable $X$ to be solved. Does MOOSE have any built-in systems that can meet such requirements?
Thanks!
Sounds like you are writing your custom scalar kernels anyways, so this should be a if-else condition. Regularize the function domain as you need.
Thanks! I'll try

Hi all,
Another question about the ODEs refered above,
$$A \cdot \frac { d ( X \cdot Y ) } { d t } = B \cdot F ( X , Y ) \quad  X \gt a$$
Could rearrange the LHS term (Time deriviate term) into,
$$A \cdot X \cdot \frac{d(Y)}{dt}+A \cdot Y \cdot \frac{d(X)}{dt}$$
So I can define a ODETimekernel about $u$ coupled with $v$ , and use it in the input deck twice wrt $X$ and $Y$ respectively.
While what about RHS? There's no way to separate two variables. Should I define it a $X$ coupled $Y$ or conversely, or both two?

I didn't quite follow why you want to separate the two variables. Is it for simplicity/modularity?
You should be able to code the exact RHS without any modification. If that doesn't work, let us know why, and we can offer suggestions.

Thank you for your respond!
Maybe I'm not being explicit. I want to define custom scalarkernel, but RHS have two inseparable variables. But how could a single scalarkernel have two variables? What I'm thinking of is defining an coupled scalarkernel. And that's why I raised the above question.
Please correct if I misunderstood something.
I see. But you can't solve two unknowns with one equation. You need two equations for two variables.

@hugary1995 Thank you again for your patience Gary!
Certain it is. In order to close this ODE, another ODE funtion is added in form like:
$$ξ ( Y ) = χ ( X , Y )$$
Which form is similar to the RHS of the ODE above, so I didn‘t mention above, but still have question like this

Hi all,
Another question about the ODEs refered above,
A⋅d(X⋅Y)dt=B⋅F(X,Y)X>a
Could rearrange the LHS term (Time deriviate term) into,
A⋅X⋅d(Y)dt+A⋅Y⋅d(X)dt
So I can define a ODETimekernel about u coupled with v , and use it in the input deck twice wrt X and Y respectively.
While what about RHS? There's no way to separate two variables. Should I define it a X coupled Y or conversely, or both two?

To be more specific, I wanna refer to the example Example 3 : Multiphysics coupling
Which has PDEs written as
$$- \nabla \cdot \nabla u + \nabla v \cdot \nabla u = 0$$
$$- \nabla \cdot \nabla v=0$$
About second term of first PDE, a convection kernel was defined on $u$ with coupled variable $v$. For me it's understandable, cause $v$ can be solved  independently by the second PDE. So when it comes to first PDE, $u$ seems to be more "dominant" than $v$, so $u$ coupled $v$ rather than $v$ coupled $u$ is defined.
But when it comes to my ODEs, variable $X$ and $Y$ have equal status, each variable cannot be determined independently by a single ODE. So I don't know what to do with ODEkernel definitions for terms like $χ ( X , Y )$. Should it be $X$ coupled $Y$ or conversely, or both two?
I’d like to apologize again for the statement that caused me confusion! I am not sure whether my statement is clear this time, and if so, any suggestions would be appreciated very much!

Okay, no problem. I think I understand now. I guess your confusion is coming from the definition of "variable" in the MOOSE input file. A lot of the times you will see something like this in the input file
[ScalarKernels]
  [foo]
    type = A
    variable = x
    coupled_variable = y
  []
  [bar]
    type = B
    variable = x
  []
  [baz]
    type = C
    variable = y
    coupled_variable = x
  []
[]
There isn't any difference between variable and coupled_variable for the purpose of retrieving values -- their variable values will be made available to you when you compute the residual and Jacobian. The value of the variable is retrieved on line 21 in "ScalarKernel.C" as _u. The coupled variable value can be retrieved (coupled) on demand using the method coupledScalarValue.
There is one important difference, however, for the purpose of assembly. One natural question to ask is: when there are multiple equations and multiple scalar variables, where do their corresponding residuals (and Jacobians) get assembled into the system of equations? The MOOSE convention is that the residual of the scalar kernels are associated with the variable of the kernel. In your case, you have two scalar equations in the following form:
Equation 1: f(X, Y) = 0
Equation 2: g(X, Y) = 0

with two unknowns X and Y. You need to tell MOOSE how to assemble the residuals. One possibility is to associate the first equation with X, and the second equation with Y, i.e.
[ScalarKernels]
  [equation1]
    type = Eq1
    variable = X
    coupled_variable = Y
  []
  [equation2]
    type = Eq2
    variable = Y
    coupled_variable = X
  []
[]
Another possibility is apparently to switch the variable and coupled_variable in each kernel. But that's a choice you have to make when you write the source code.

Okay, I'll try again. In fact, I have already defined according custom scalerkernel.
To be specific


$$A \cdot X \cdot \frac { d ( Y ) } { d t } + A \cdot Y \cdot \frac { d ( X ) } { d t }$$
Defined according kernel, time derivative term as variable and another as coupled_variable, using twice in the input respectively


$$x ( X , Y )$$ $$F ( X , Y )$$
Defined according kernel, using once in the input with $X$ as variable and $Y$ as coupled_variable


But the calculated resudial doesn't deccrease, looks like the equation is not closed, so I have above question.
I will try more, this may take some time, I will update if there is any result.
It's a system of 2 dofs, so I'd just print out the Jacobian (a 2-by-2 matrix) to verify.

@hugary1995 My custom kernels runs successfully and get correct result according your guidance

with two unknowns X and Y. You need to tell MOOSE how to assemble the residuals. One possibility is to associate the first equation with X, and the second equation with Y, i.e.

There were other non-convergence problems among the process, which turned out to be due to zero jacobian. I solved the problem by defining zero Jacobian as a small value as Issue #23594  suggests.
Thank you again for your professional guidance and patience Gary!

node.title: how are constant monomial aux variables computed from material properties?
node.bodyText:
How are these calculated? Is it just a simple algebraic mean (sum(values)/N) over the qp's on the element? Does the element volume come into play? Or is there some kind of integral involving a shape function?
Specifically I'm using the Tensor Mechanics Master Action to generate constant monomial auxvariables from stresses, but those are just  material properties so the same logic should apply I'm guessing?
What kind of quadrature rule is involved for this?

That's actually a good question. Ideally, one should be able to pick a quadrature rule. But MOOSE has taken the monopoly decision here -- all objects (kernels, auxkernels, materials, userobjects, etc.) use the same quadrature rule.
The default quadrature rule should be Gauss quadrature, the order is determined by the maximum variable order.
The quadrature defined in the executioner. By default GAUSS with an order sufficient to integrate exactly the shape function * test function (polynomials) products
so would it be the same quadrature used for the nonlinear system variables?

node.title: AD version of ComputeThermalExpansionEigenstrain with temperature dependent coefficient
node.bodyText:
Hi,
I am trying to compute thermal expansion eigen strain $\epsilon=\alpha(T)(T-T_0)I$. I see there are two ways:

In #21785, ComputeVariableEigenstrain (I believe that is the new name for the object ComputeVariableDependentEigenstrainmentioned previously). The issue with this one is that it is non-AD. Do we have a AD version of it?
what I want is very close to what MOOSE already have, Compute Thermal Expansion Eigenstrain, where it implements $\epsilon=\alpha(T-T_0)I$. The adaptation seems not complicated since it supports AD already: re-define  ADComputeThermalExpansionEigenstrain\thermal_expansion_coeff to be ADMaterialProperty<Real> instead of Real, then use ADParsedMaterial to define such a material.

I want to know which way is better. If 2 is better and no one is considering adding such feature, I can open an issue and submit a PR for it.
@bwspenc @dschwen @jiangwen84 do you have a suggestion for @BoZeng1997 ?
Have you looked at ComputeMeanThermalExpansionFunctionEigenstrain?  You can use temperature dependent thermal expansion.

@jiangwen84 Hi! Thanks for the recommendation. I am running simulation with ComputeMeanThermalExpansionFunctionEigenstrain.  From the description on the webage, T_ref is a required parameter and usually is different from stress free temperature. I could not find T_ref for my material's thermal expansion coefficient data. But I dont see a problem in my simulation when setting the same value for both parameters. What is your advice on it?

In the second equation on the MOOSE documentation page (https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/materials/ComputeMeanThermalExpansionFunctionEigenstrain.html#!), if you set T_sf = T_ref, then you basically get
epsilon = alpha (T-T_sf), which might be something you want.
In general, the T_sf and T_ref are different. You can also read this paper for more information https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0029549311010387?ref=cra_js_challenge&fr=RR-1
thanks. that is very helpful!

node.title: Does RACCOON require pre-defined cracks?
node.bodyText:
Hi,
As the title says, when modelling using RACCOON, does the model require a pre-defined crack?
If not, is there any example code i can look at where it shows a new crack forming?
Thanks and cheers.
@hugary1995
(if there are others knowledgeable please let me know so I can spread the tagging)

You could also tag @jiangwen84 for phase field fracture (RACCOON) questions. I'm a little behind on other stuff so I probably won't monitor this discussion page frequently enough.
@NeedOfHelp pre-defined crack in which representation? Regularized (phase-field) crack or sharp crack (mesh discontinuity)?
For a regularized crack, there are a few initial condition objects in RACCOON you can play with. More generally speaking, you can use any MOOSE initial condition object to set the initial phase field.
For a sharp crack, you need to prepare a meshed-in crack.

Thanks for your reply.
I was thinking more in phase-field modelling of cracks. I have seen your tutorial codes on fracture and all of them seems to have a pre-defined crack, as far as I have seen.
So I started wondering how the simulations would go if the crack was defined in the middle, the sides, two cracks at the same time and also what if there were no initial crack at all?
I'm a new user to RACCOON and MOOSE and I'm trying to learn my way up, so I am kinda clueless on what types of modules/packages that exists.
Cheers.
